Validation of eating and dieting expectancy measures in two adolescent samples.

Simmons JR(1), Smith GT, Hill KK.

Author information:
(1)The Cleveland Clinic, Cleveland, Ohio, USA.

OBJECTIVE: To demonstrate the validity of two measures of eating and dieting 
expectancies (The Eating Expectancy Inventory [EEI] and the Thinness and 
Restricting Expectancy Inventory, [TREI]) for use with adolescents.
METHOD: Seventh (N = 392) and tenth graders (N = 300) completed the Bulimia 
Test-Revised (BULIT-R), the Eating Disorder Inventory (EDI-II), and two factors 
of the Three-Factor Eating Questionnaire (TFEQ).
RESULTS: Findings replicated for the two adolescent samples. The expectancy that 
thinness leads to overgeneralized life improvement correlated with measures of 
"successful" dieting, dieting plus disinhibition, and bulimic symptomatology. 
